<p class=""><h2>Key Challenges in the Myasthenia Gravis Market</h2><ul>    <li>        <strong>Limited Awareness:</strong>        <p>Myasthenia Gravis (MG) is often underdiagnosed due to its rarity and the variability of symptoms. This lack of awareness among healthcare providers can delay treatment and worsen patient outcomes.</p>    </li>    <li>        <strong>Complexity of Diagnosis:</strong>        <p>Diagnosing MG requires a range of specialized tests, such as antibody tests and electrophysiological studies, which can be time-consuming and may not be readily available in all healthcare settings.</p>    </li>    <li>        <strong>High Treatment Costs:</strong>        <p>The costs associated with long-term management of MG, including immunosuppressants and other therapies, can impose a financial burden on patients and healthcare systems alike.</p>    </li>    <li>        <strong>Adverse Effects of Treatments:</strong>        <p>Current treatment options can have significant side effects, leading to treatment discontinuation or reduced adherence, which negatively impacts patient quality of life and disease management.</p>    </li>    <li>        <strong>Lack of Novel Treatments:</strong>        <p>The pipeline for innovative therapies is relatively thin, limiting options for patients who do not respond well to existing medications. This gap presents a substantial barrier to improvement in patient outcomes.</p>    </li></ul><h2>Potential Growth Opportunities in the Myasthenia Gravis Market</h2><ul>    <li>        <strong>Advancements in Biomarker Research:</strong>        <p>The identification of new biomarkers could facilitate earlier diagnosis and more personalized treatment options. This would not only improve patient management but also create potential opportunities for biopharmaceutical companies.</p>    </li>    <li>        <strong>Development of Targeted Therapies:</strong>        <p>            There is a growing interest in developing targeted therapie